Rating: 4
This is always a hit evertime I make it. It takes closer to an hour and a half to bake if you have a gas stove and I usually use less butter and a dash more salt when I make it. It's also extremely important to let it cool before serving, the more it is set the better the taste.

Rating: 3
Easy to do; got great raves at our neighborhood Thanksgiving Dinner. But it takes a little longer than 45-minutes to bake.

Rating: 3
This has become a staple at every holdiay gathering in our family. The vanilla bean is what makes is so special, I think. I make this the night before and partially bake it ( about 25-30 minutes). It should be set up about 3/4 of the way through, but not brown, dry or tough around the edges. Then I refrigerate and finish baking the next day. (another 20 minutes at 350) This way I can take it to a gathering without any fuss. I also reduce the amount of butter- the full amount in the recipe leaves a lot of butter at the top after cooking.

Rating: 3
I really like this dish...and I typically don't like corn pudding. I don't know how they fit it into a pie or quiche pan; I had to use a lasagna pan. I used 2% milk. The second time I made it I cut the butter to 3 tablespoons and liked it much better.